# Documentation: aligned table of contents

When you add or edit **project documentation** in Markdown (`README.md`, `docs/**/*.md`, `CHANGELOG.md`, etc.):

1. **Include a TOC** near the top: after the H1 title and any one-line blurb, add `## Table of Contents` before the first real content section.
2. **Keep it aligned**: Every `##` section in the file appears as a TOC bullet **in the same order**, with an anchor link. Skip only headings that are not meant to be navigated (never link `## Table of Contents` itself).
3. **Update in lockstep**: Renaming, adding, removing, or moving headings requires updating the TOC in the **same change**.
4. **Anchors**: Use standard GitHub-style slugs: lower case, spaces → `-`, strip most punctuation, collapse duplicate hyphens (e.g. `## Quick Start (Consumer Repo)` → `#quick-start-consumer-repo`).
5. **Depth**: For files with only `##`, list those. If you introduce meaningful `###` sections that readers jump to, extend the TOC consistently for that file (either all key `###` or none—avoid a partial random subset).

```markdown
## Table of Contents

- [Purpose](#purpose)
- [Setup](#setup)
```

When asked to write or refactor MD docs, apply this by default unless the file is trivial (e.g. a few lines with no `##` sections—in that case no TOC is required).
